Implement R2 of s-9ymk: fit SVG along its shortest side (CSS object-fit: cover semantics).

## Implementation

In `src/diagram-canvas.js#setDimensionsAndScale` (currently line 341):

```js
const scaleX = (viewerW - padding) / width;
const scaleY = (viewerH - padding) / height;
// Cover fit: scale so the shortest side of the content fully matches the
// corresponding viewport side. The longer side overflows and is reachable
// via the existing scroll container. Equivalent to CSS `object-fit: cover`.
const fitScale = Math.max(scaleX, scaleY);
```

Replace `Math.min` with `Math.max` and add the comment block above the calculation explaining cover-fit semantics.

## Acceptance

- The `transform: scale(...)` assertion in i-8w67 passes for the cover-fit formula.
- Manual smoke test: a tall SVG (e.g. `Nodes/index.svg` 1202×2468) loaded in a wide viewport now overflows vertically (scrollable) and fills the viewport horizontally — not letterboxed.
- A wide SVG (e.g. 1200×400) loaded in a narrow viewport overflows horizontally and fills vertically.

## Notes

- Do NOT change the default zoom level here (that is i-jxxx). After this change, zoom 1.5 (current default) will overflow significantly — expected and addressed by the next issue.

